<font color="#FF0000">ON THE IMPORTANCE OF THREADS..</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jul 26 23:29:06 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Arthur, and Mr. Ramon: No I do not wish to control this wonderful site. BUT, if a new thread is openned for every poem, or every story, then we will strangle this site. That is my concern.  I asked Robt, another poetic, to group his poems and he did. It makes for a better read for the reader, and a chance to see all the work in one thread. Check out is thread, and you will see what I mean. It is so much more powerful for the writer, the poet, to have his work together in one place, or one thread, and for the reader to enjoy it all in one place.  Not spread out among the parking lot brawl and dog droppings.  I know you guys will agree if you will drop your anger at me and thing about the common good.<br><br>
I fear that we will destroy this site if everyone opens a thread for every poem, or every thought, or every counter point.  So, Art, yes I want to be a controller I guess. I didn't plan on that. More of wanting to be a protector I guess. I want to protect this site, and the IMPORTANCE of each and every theard, even those from Cook B. <br><br>
Mr. Ramon, please group your poems into one thread, and not pick a new thread for each poem. To me that is the height of egotism.  A thread is a site within a site for discussion, for thought, for introspection, and finally, for learning and growth.  Let us all not CLOG the site with our vanity. PLEASE.  Hell, I too have been writing poety since the 60's, and I have a soon to be published novel, but I won't clog the site with it.  I hope the rest of you will have the same consideration.  This is a place to talk, and to grow, to fight and to hug, to get on with our lives, not our egos.  <br><br>
Come on lads, join me in this, regardless of our differences.<br><br>
doc spatz
